ex001.name: Dumbbell Incline Bench Press
ex001.instructions: Set the bench to a low incline (30 degrees). Lie back and pinch your shoulder blades together so your chest sticks out. When you lower the weights, tuck your elbows in at a 45-degree angle (like an arrow), don't flare them out wide (like a T). Lower the weights until they touch your outer chest, then press up. Stop just before your elbows lock out to keep the tension on your chest.

ex002.name: Leg Extension
ex002.instructions: Sit in the machine and adjust the pad so it sits right on your ankles/shins. Hold the handles tight to keep your butt in the seat. Kick your legs up until they are straight and squeeze your quads hard at the top. Lower the weight slowly—don't let the stack slam down.

ex003.name: Pull Up
ex003.instructions: Grab the bar slightly wider than shoulder-width. initiate the movement by driving your elbows down toward your ribs, not by pulling with your biceps. pulling your chest all the way to the bar.
ex003.notes: Best back width builder (or Lat Pulldown)

ex004.name: Cable Lateral Raise
ex004.instructions: Set the cable pulley to the very bottom. Stand sideways to the machine. Grab the handle with the hand furthest away from the machine. Step out so the weight stack is lifted slightly even when your arm is down. Lift your arm out to the side, leading with your elbow, not your hand. Think about pushing your knuckles toward the wall, not the ceiling. Stop when your arm is parallel to the floor.
ex004.notes: CRITICAL: Creates shoulder width and V-taper

ex005.name: Dumbbell Shoulder Press
ex005.instructions: Sit with the bench almost vertical (about 75 degrees) so you have back support. Kick the weights up to your shoulders. Press straight up overhead until your arms are straight. On the way down, control the weight all the way until the dumbbells actually touch your shoulders. Don't stop at ear level—that’s a half rep. Keep your core tight so you don't arch your lower back too much.

ex006.name: Back Squat
ex006.instructions: Put the bar on your traps (not your neck). Step back, set your feet shoulder-width apart, toes pointed slightly out. Take a huge breath into your stomach and brace your abs. Break at the hips and knees at the same time. Sit down until the crease of your hip is below the top of your knee. Drive back up through the middle of your foot. Keep your knees pushed out; don't let them cave in.

ex007.name: Standing Machine Calf Press
ex007.instructions: Put the balls of your feet on the edge of the platform. Lower your heels as far down as physically possible—this stretch is the most important part. Pause for a second at the bottom. Then push up onto your big toes. Don't bounce.
ex007.notes: Full stretch at bottom, pause at top

ex008.name: Seated Leg Curl
ex008.instructions: Sit in the machine and clamp the thigh pad down tight so your legs can't move. Kick your legs down and back under you. Squeeze at the bottom. Control the weight on the way up. Don't use momentum to jerk the weight down.

ex009.name: Cable Crunch
ex009.instructions: Use the rope attachment on a high pulley. Kneel down facing the machine. Hold the rope next to your ears. Crunch down by aiming your forehead toward your knees. Visualize curling your spine like a shrimp. Don't just bend at the hips—your back *should* round on this one to contract the abs. Exhale all your air as you crunch down.

ex012.name: Lat Pulldown
ex012.instructions: Sit down, jam your knees under the pad so you don't float up. Lean back just a tiny bit, and pull the bar to your upper chest. Control it on the way up.

ex014.name: Incline Dumbbell Curl
ex014.instructions: Set the bench to a high incline (45-60 degrees). Sit back and let your arms hang straight down behind your torso. This stretches the bicep head. Curl the weights up while keeping your elbows pointed at the floor. Don't swing your elbows forward.

ex017.name: Dumbbell Bench Press
ex017.instructions: Same mechanics as the incline press, just on a flat bench. Pinch your shoulder blades back. Tuck elbows at 45 degrees. Lower until the dumbbells touch near your armpits/outer chest. Press back up.

ex021.name: Cable Rope Overhead Triceps Extension
ex021.instructions: Set the cable pulley to about waist height (or lower). Grab the rope, turn away from the machine, and press the rope overhead. Your elbows should stay pointing at the ceiling the whole time. Only your forearms move. Lower the rope behind your head until you feel a deep stretch in your triceps, then extend your arms straight up. Flare your hands out at the top.

ex025.name: Romanian Deadlift
ex025.instructions: Hold a barbell or dumbbells standing tall. Keep your legs slightly bent (soft knees), but lock them in that position—your knees shouldn't bend any more than that. Push your hips backward like you are trying to close a car door with your butt. Keep the weight sliding down your thighs. Go down until you feel a massive stretch in your hamstrings (usually mid-shin). Squeeze your glutes to stand back up. Keep your back flat the entire time.

ex033.name: Machine Rear Delt Fly
ex033.instructions: Sit facing the machine. Adjust the handles so they are fully to the rear. Grab the handles with your palms facing each other or down (whatever feels better). Keep a slight bend in your elbows. Push your hands out and back in a wide arc. Squeeze the back of your shoulders. Don't let your shoulders shrug up toward your ears.
ex033.notes: Rear delt and rotator cuff health

ex055.name: Dip
ex055.instructions: Jump up on the bars. To target your chest, lean your torso forward (look at the ground). Lower yourself until your shoulders are slightly below your elbows. Push back up. Keep your shoulders packed down (away from your ears) the whole time so you don't hurt your neck.

ex083.name: Single-arm Dumbbell Row
ex083.instructions: Find a flat bench. Put your left knee and left hand on the bench. Your back should be flat like a table. Grab the dumbbell with your right hand. Pull the weight back toward your hip pocket, not straight up to your armpit. Think about dragging your elbow back. Lower it all the way down until you feel a stretch in your lat.

ex138.name: Chest-Supported Dumbbell Incline Row
ex138.instructions: Set an incline bench to 30 or 45 degrees. Lie face down on it with a dumbbell in each hand. Let your arms hang straight down. Pull the weights up by driving your elbows back and squeezing your shoulder blades together. Since your chest is supported, don't let your body swing or lift off the pad. It's all back.

ex140.name: Barbell Shrug
ex140.instructions: Hold a barbell (or heavy dumbbells) with straight arms. Shrug your shoulders straight up toward your ears. Hold it at the very top for a full second. Lower it slowly. Don't roll your shoulders forward or backward—just go straight up and down.
